[C]
Date: 15 Jun 2003
From: ProMED-mail
Source: Newsday 14 Jun 2003 [Edited]
<http://www.newsday.com/news/health/ny-lisars143332355jun14,0,5598067.story?
coll=ny-health-headlines>
A 52-year-old Nassau woman has become the first person suspected of
contracting SARS within New York State, health officials said Friday. The
health care worker is believed to have been exposed while overseeing a
patient hospitalized with possible SARS.
All of the other individuals in the state with a suspect or probable SARS
diagnosis are believed to have acquired it during travel to endemic regions,
such as China or Canada. There are 59 possible cases across the state,
including one in Suffolk County & 7 in Nassau County. All of the others on
Long Island are reported to have recovered.
[By Dawn MacKeen]
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[In North Carolina, it has become less likely that any local transmission of
SARS has occurred. The discovery of an apparent "missing link" between the
1st Toronto outbreak and the delayed 2nd outbreak is actually reassuring, in
that there is no need to invoke some undiscovered mechanism of transmission
or an unknown focus in the community -- although the source of the infection
in the psychiatric ward is unclear. More information is awaited on the Long
Island, NY case. - Mod.LM/JW]
